  "response_text": "The commercial opens on a wooden office desk in a dim, plain office setting. A white nameplate on the front of the desk reads “SALES DIRECTOR.” On the desktop are papers, a pen holder, small desk accessories, and a few rectangular office items. Behind the desk sits a middle-aged white man with neatly combed dark hair, wearing a dark business suit, light shirt, red striped tie, and a white pocket square. He holds his hands up near his face at first, as if rubbing his forehead or bracing himself, then lowers them and leans forward toward the viewer with a stern, concerned expression, playing the role of the sales director.\n\nThe scene changes to a staged showroom-like space with a dark background and a light floor. A large triangular hanging sign dominates the background. It reads “FACTORY AUTHORIZED” at the top, “SALE” in very large orange letters across the middle, and “PHILCO” near the bottom, with a small blue oval Ford emblem beside it. Two wood-cabinet television sets stand beneath the sign: a smaller set on the left and a larger console television on the right. The same suited man walks in from the right, moving between the televisions and the sale sign. He gestures downward and outward with both hands toward the sets, especially the smaller one at first, then stands centered between them as if presenting the products. His posture is formal but animated, and his face suggests irritation or disbelief.\n\nThe larger console television is then shown more closely. It is a wood-finished cabinet set on short angled legs, with a large rounded rectangular screen on the left and a vertical control panel with knobs on the right. A white sale tag hangs on or near the lower right front of the television, visibly showing a price connected to “480,” matching the spoken sale-price context. The man’s legs and one hand are partly visible beside the set, with his hand resting near the top edge, directing attention to the television.\n\nThe man appears in a closer view in front of the giant orange-and-white “SALE” lettering. His face fills much of the picture, with the bold sale sign blurred but readable behind him. He continues addressing the viewer directly. He points and pumps one fist slightly as he emphasizes features and price, then briefly opens his eyes wide and raises his eyebrows, creating an exaggerated look of surprise. His expression shifts between firm, exasperated, and almost forced enthusiasm, reinforcing the idea that he is reluctantly announcing a very good sale.\n\nHe then looks down and to his side, bending forward slightly, as if reacting uneasily to what he has just said. The commercial cuts back to the large Philco console television. The wood cabinet and screen are centered, the sale tag remains attached on the lower right, and small white text appears along the bottom of the picture; it is faint but reads like a manufacturer’s suggested retail sale-price note. The set remains stationary and prominently displayed, with the man’s dark trouser leg and hand still partly visible at the left edge.\n\nThe final moments return to the man in front of the oversized “SALE” background. He faces forward, then glances aside and downward again. His expression grows more troubled and queasy-looking, with his mouth tightening and his brow furrowing, as if the sale price pains him personally. He remains in his dark suit and striped tie against the bold orange sale lettering, ending the commercial with the sales director visually looking uncomfortable about the bargain being offered.",
